`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"Event-Driven Architecture (EDA) is a powerful paradigm that enables systems to be more flexible, scalable, and resilient by decoupling components and allowing them to communicate through events. Throughout this article, we’ve explored the principles of EDA, discussed its core concepts like deferred execution, eventual consistency, choreography, and CQRS, and demonstrated how these concepts can be applied in practice using Redis and a custom-built CLI tool."}),`
`,n.jsx(e.p,{children:"By embracing EDA, you can design systems that not only handle complex workflows efficiently but also adapt to changing demands with ease. Whether you're scaling query services, coordinating actions through events, or ensuring eventual consistency in distributed systems, EDA provides the tools and patterns to build robust architectures."}),`
